amdgpu: gmc_v7 — Liverpool/Gladius custom vmid 4 PD for UVD bring-up

Round 3 hardware test of v0061 (VC4 DEPTH=0) exposed a structural truth:
GCN1/gmc_v7 has NO per-VMID CNTL register (VC[2-15]_CNTL doesn't exist
in the chip's register layout). All vmids 1..15 share VC1_CNTL settings
as a template. So my v0061 attempt to "set VC4 to depth=0" actually
wrote to mmVM_CONTEXT0_CNTL2 at offset 0x508 (the correct VC4_CNTL doesn't
exist), corrupting VC0's secondary fault config — that's why GFX failed
-110 in v0061 hardware test.

Sony's gbase model (decompile of FUN_c886a540 in gc/vm.c) allocates a
SEPARATE PD per VMID. Each vmid gets its own PT_BASE pointing at its
own PD that walks correctly under VC1's depth=1 template.

Linux mainline doesn't have an equivalent. This patch implements the
smallest viable form for Liverpool/Gladius UVD bring-up:

  1. Allocate a 4 KB PD for vmid 4.
  2. Use mmVM_CONTEXT4_PAGE_TABLE_START_ADDR to shift the PDE index
     origin to VA 0x300000000 (where Sony's UVD firmware does its
     fixed reads). Without START_ADDR shifting, PDE 6144 would be
     needed → 49 KB PD allocation; with it, just PDE[0] and PDE[1].
  3. Trick: PDE format = PTE format on GCN1. Point PDE entries at
     chunks of the EXISTING GART table where patches 0042-44 already
     bound the firmware mirror at GART VA 0x300000000. The "PT" the
     walker reaches is actually GART entries — same format, valid
     firmware physical addresses already populated.

PDE values (table_addr = amdgpu_bo_gpu_offset(adev->gart.bo)):
  PDE[0] = (table_addr + 0x300000*8) | 1   → covers VA 0x300000000-0x300200000
  PDE[1] = (table_addr + 0x300200*8) | 1   → covers VA 0x300200000-0x300400000

Two PDEs cover 4 MB of VA; firmware is 3.1 MB. END_ADDR = page 0x300400.

Does NOT touch VC1_CNTL — leaves GFX vmid 1 at DEPTH=1/block_size for
amdgpu_vm per-process PDs. Avoids the v0061 GFX regression (which was
actually caused by writing to mmVM_CONTEXT0_CNTL2 at 0x508, not VC4_CNTL).

Test plan:
  - Watch for "vmid 4 custom PD @ GPU 0x...PDE[0]=0x...PDE[1]=0x..."
  - GFX should init cleanly (no -110)
  - UVD's uvd_v4_2_start_liverpool should run, write LMI_VM_VBASE,
    release VCPU. With vmid 4 PT walks now succeeding, STATUS bit 1
    should fire, ring test should pass.

Risk:
  - GART entries used as PT entries assumes their format is identical.
    On GCN1 PTE/PDE share bit layout (page addr in bits 12+, flags in
    low bits). If firmware reads need protection bits other than what
    0042-44 set (READABLE | WRITEABLE | VALID | SYSTEM), need to update
    those bindings too.
  - PD lifetime: BO is `static`, leaks if amdgpu unloads. Acceptable
    for kernel-lifetime allocation; not a regression.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
@@ -745,6 +745,76 @@
 	WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT1_CNTL, tmp);
 
 	/*
+	 * 2026-05-16 v0062: PS4 Liverpool/Gladius custom vmid 4 PD for UVD.
+	 *
+	 * Round 3 dig (Sony gbase_map in gc/vm.c) revealed mainline points
+	 * vmid 4's PT_BASE at the shared flat GART PD, but VC1_CNTL forces
+	 * 2-level walks (DEPTH=1). GCN1 has NO per-VMID CNTL register
+	 * (VC[2-15]_CNTL doesn't exist) — all vmids 1..15 share VC1's
+	 * settings as a template. So vmid 4 walks GART flat-PD as if 2-level,
+	 * gets garbage PDE values, and faults at UVD fw read of VA 0x300000000.
+	 *
+	 * Sony allocates per-VMID PDs (gbase_create_vmid). Linux mainline
+	 * doesn't have an equivalent. We replicate the smallest viable form:
+	 *
+	 *   - Allocate a tiny PD (1 page, only 2 PDEs used).
+	 *   - Use mmVM_CONTEXT4_PAGE_TABLE_START_ADDR to shift the PDE
+	 *     index origin to 0x300000000 (otherwise PDE 6144 needs a
+	 *     49 KB PD).
+	 *   - PDE format = PTE format on GCN1 — so we can point PDE entries
+	 *     into chunks of the existing GART table where 0042-44 already
+	 *     bound the firmware mirror. The "PT" the walker reaches is
+	 *     actually GART entries (PTE-format, firmware physical addresses).
+	 *
+	 *   PDE[0] = (gart_table_addr + 0x300000*8) | 1
+	 *     → walker reads PT at GART byte offset 0x1800000 = GART page
+	 *       0x300000 entry = firmware page 0 (VA 0x300000000)
+	 *   PDE[1] = (gart_table_addr + 0x300200*8) | 1
+	 *     → walker reads PT at GART byte offset 0x1801000 = GART page
+	 *       0x300200 entry = firmware page 0x200 (VA 0x300200000)
+	 *
+	 * Two PDEs cover 4 MB of VA (firmware is 3.1 MB, fits).
+	 * VC4_END_ADDR set to 0x300400 (page) = VA 0x300400000.
+	 * Does NOT touch VC1_CNTL — leaves GFX vmid 1 at DEPTH=1 / block_size
+	 * for amdgpu_vm. Avoids the v0061 GFX regression (which was actually
+	 * caused by writing to mmVM_CONTEXT0_CNTL2 at 0x508, not VC4_CNTL).
+	 */
+	if (adev->asic_type == CHIP_LIVERPOOL || adev->asic_type == CHIP_GLADIUS) {
+		static struct amdgpu_bo *ps4_vmid4_pd_bo;
+		u64 pd_gpu_addr;
+		void *pd_cpu;
+		int r;
+
+		r = amdgpu_bo_create_kernel(adev, PAGE_SIZE, PAGE_SIZE,
+					    AMDGPU_GEM_DOMAIN_VRAM,
+					    &ps4_vmid4_pd_bo,
+					    &pd_gpu_addr, &pd_cpu);
+		if (!r && pd_cpu) {
+			u64 *pd = (u64 *)pd_cpu;
+
+			memset(pd, 0, PAGE_SIZE);
+			/* PDE format on GCN1 = PTE format: addr | flags (bit 0 = valid) */
+			pd[0] = (table_addr + 0x300000ULL * 8) | 1;
+			pd[1] = (table_addr + 0x300200ULL * 8) | 1;
+
+			WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT4_PAGE_TABLE_BASE_ADDR,
+			       pd_gpu_addr >> 12);
+			WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT0_PAGE_TABLE_START_ADDR + 4,
+			       0x300000ULL);
+			WREG32(mmVM_CONTEXT0_PAGE_TABLE_END_ADDR + 4,
+			       0x300400ULL);
+
+			DRM_INFO("ps4 gmc_v7: vmid 4 custom PD @ GPU 0x%llx, "
+				 "PDE[0]=0x%016llx PDE[1]=0x%016llx, "
+				 "VA range [0x300000000, 0x300400000)\n",
+				 pd_gpu_addr, pd[0], pd[1]);
+		} else {
+			DRM_WARN("ps4 gmc_v7: vmid 4 custom PD alloc failed (%d); "
+				 "UVD VCPU will still fault\n", r);
+		}
+	}
+
+	/*
 	 * v76d-β-2-A: Liverpool/Gladius UVD page-table fix.
 	 *
 	 * Upstream sets PAGE_TABLE_DEPTH=1 for VC1 (which propagates to
